======================================================================
DISC-8 PHASE 1, ITEM 2: VP SINGLE-THRESHOLD CLOSURE
======================================================================

THEOREM: The VP running between adjacent thresholds has no
periodic structure under any smooth change of variables.

PROOF:

  Between two adjacent mass thresholds m_f and m_{f+1},
  the coupling runs as:

    alpha^{-1}(mu) = alpha^{-1}(m_f) + (b/2pi) * ln(mu/m_f)

  Define kappa = ln(mu/m_f). Then:

    alpha^{-1}(kappa) = alpha^{-1}(0) + c * kappa

  where c = b/(2pi) is a positive constant (for asymptotic freedom).

  This is a LINEAR function of kappa: f(kappa) = a + c*kappa.

  Claim: No smooth bijection g: R -> R makes f(g(x)) periodic.

  Proof: Suppose f(g(x)) = a + c*g(x) is periodic with period P.
  Then f(g(x+P)) = f(g(x)) for all x.
  So a + c*g(x+P) = a + c*g(x).
  So g(x+P) = g(x) for all x.
  But g is a bijection (invertible), and a periodic function
  is not injective (g(0) = g(P) = g(2P) = ...).
  Contradiction. QED.

  The argument extends: ANY monotonic function composed with
  ANY bijection remains non-periodic, because periodicity
  requires the function to return to a previous value,
  which a monotonic-composed-with-bijection cannot do.

RESULT: The Q5 null from DISC-7 is CLOSED DEFINITIVELY.
  Not just for the full VP running (unequal thresholds),
  but for each single-threshold segment individually.
  The VP running is structurally monotonic at every scale.
  No change of variables can introduce periodicity.

  Subgroup B (monotonic accumulation) is IRREDUCIBLY
  distinct from Subgroup A (phase-periodic).
  The separation is topological: monotonic vs periodic
  is a property preserved under all smooth coordinate changes.

